#compdef redsmin
# ============================================================================
# redsmin - Redsmin proxy daemon for connecting
#            local/firewalled Redis instances to
#            the Redsmin SaaS GUI (Node.js, MIT)
#
# Author : Francois-Guillaume Ribreau (FGRibreau)
# Upstream: https://github.com/Redsmin/proxy
# npm    : redsmin (binary: redsmin)
# Homepage: https://redsmin.com
#
# `redsmin` is the Redsmin Proxy daemon - a TLS-
# encrypted tunneling proxy that exposes a local
# or firewalled Redis instance to the Redsmin
# SaaS Redis GUI (https://redsmin.com). Redsmin
# is a hosted Redis management dashboard;
# customers run the redsmin proxy on their own
# infrastructure + the proxy establishes an
# outbound TLS connection to ssl.redsmin.com:993
# that the Redsmin frontend tunnels Redis
# commands over.
#
# Architecture:
#   - Node stdlib `tls` for outbound TLS
#     connection to Redsmin cloud endpoint
#   - Node stdlib `net` for local Redis client
#     connections
#   - common-env for environment-variable-based
#     configuration
#   - update-notifier for npm update prompts
#   - Per-Redis-connection multiplexing over a
#     single TLS tunnel (one proxy can manage
#     multiple Redis instances)
#
# Use cases:
#   - Expose firewalled/private Redis instances
#     to Redsmin's web GUI without opening
#     inbound ports
#   - Cloud-Redis-management for IaC/CI-deployed
#     Redis instances (Redis on AWS ElastiCache /
#     Azure Redis / GCP Memorystore via Redsmin
#     frontend)
#   - Multi-Redis-instance management from a
#     single browser tab
#
# Usage:
#   redsmin
#
# This binary takes NO command-line flags - all
# configuration is via environment variables or
# a JSON config file. The redsmin proxy is
# designed for daemon-style deployment + reads
# its configuration once at startup.
#
# Environment variables (read via common-env;
# default values shown):
#   CONFIG_FILE                   - path to JSON
#                                    config file
#                                    (default
#                                    /path/to/
#                                    redsmin/etc/
#                                    redsmin.json)
#   DEBUG                         - enable debug
#                                    logging
#                                    (default
#                                    false)
#   REDSMIN_KEY                   - Redsmin
#                                    server
#                                    connection
#                                    key (24
#                                    hex chars;
#                                    obtained
#                                    from
#                                    redsmin.com
#                                    dashboard;
#                                    required)
#   REDSMIN_HOSTNAME              - Redsmin
#                                    cloud
#                                    endpoint
#                                    (default
#                                    ssl.redsmin.
#                                    com)
#   REDSMIN_PORT                  - Redsmin
#                                    cloud port
#                                    (default
#                                    993)
#   REDSMIN_REJECT_UNAUTHORIZED   - verify TLS
#                                    certificate
#                                    chain
#                                    (default 1
#                                    = strict;
#                                    set to 0
#                                    only for
#                                    debugging
#                                    with
#                                    self-
#                                    signed
#                                    certs)
#   REDIS_URI                     - local Redis
#                                    URI
#                                    (default
#                                    redis://
#                                    127.0.0.1:
#                                    6379;
#                                    supports
#                                    redis://,
#                                    rediss://,
#                                    unix:// URI
#                                    schemes)
#   REDIS_AUTH                    - Redis
#                                    password
#                                    (default
#                                    null;
#                                    required
#                                    if Redis
#                                    instance
#                                    has AUTH)
#
# Example deployment:
#   REDSMIN_KEY=abc123...xyz REDIS_URI=redis://127.0.0.1:6379 \
#     npx redsmin
#
#   # Or via Docker (canonical deployment):
#   docker run -d --name redsmin -e REDSMIN_KEY=abc123...xyz \
#     -e REDIS_URI=redis://redis-host:6379 \
#     redsmin/proxy
#
# Example etc/redsmin.json config file (loaded
# if CONFIG_FILE is set):
#   {
#     "debug": false,
#     "redsmin": {
#       "port": 993,
#       "hostname": "ssl.redsmin.com",
#       "reject_unauthorized": 1,
#       "key": "abc123def456789abcdef012"
#     },
#     "redis": {
#       "uri": "redis://127.0.0.1:6379",
#       "auth": null
#     }
#   }
#
# The tls lane is built on Node's stdlib `tls`
# module (imported as `var tls = require('tls')`
# in app.js line 12, then passed to the
# `Endpoint` + `RedisClient` modules for
# establishing outbound TLS connections to
# ssl.redsmin.com:993 via `tls.connect(port,
# host, options)` for the Redsmin cloud-tunnel
# endpoint). The `tls` module is part of Node's
# core runtime + ships with every Node
# distribution.
#
# Node's `tls` stdlib module:
#   - Implemented as a JavaScript layer over a
#     C++ binding that wraps OpenSSL (or the
#     BoringSSL fork in some Node builds)
#   - The OpenSSL version is bundled into Node
#     itself (the `process.versions.openssl`
#     property reports the bundled version)
#   - TLS 1.2 + TLS 1.3 support
#   - Client + server modes (`tls.connect()` for
#     clients + `tls.createServer()` for
#     servers)
#   - ALPN (Application-Layer Protocol
#     Negotiation) for HTTP/2 + HTTP/3 +
#     custom protocols
#   - SNI (Server Name Indication) for virtual
#     hosting
#   - Session resumption (session IDs + tickets
#     in TLS 1.2 + PSK in TLS 1.3)
#   - Configurable cert verification + custom CA
#     bundles
#   - secureContext objects for connection-level
#     TLS configuration
#
# Node's tls distinguishing features vs
# alternatives:
#   - node:tls (stdlib): canonical; OpenSSL
#     wrapper; THIS AXIS
#   - rustls-node: WIP Node bindings for Rust's
#     rustls
#   - tls-extension: pure-JS TLS in some
#     restricted contexts
#   - The native node:crypto + node:tls
#     combination is the canonical Node TLS
#     pair
#
# Node's stdlib-first culture for TLS is
# inherited from Node's design philosophy:
# the core runtime ships with batteries-included
# I/O including TLS. The Node team maintains
# `node:tls` alongside the rest of the runtime,
# with the OpenSSL version updated via Node's
# release cycle.
#
# Node's `tls` module governance:
#   - Maintained by the Node.js project core
#     team (including James M Snell + Anna
#     Henningsen + Matteo Collina + many
#     others)
#   - OpenSSL updates tracked via Node's
#     release schedule (Node 18+ ships OpenSSL
#     3.0; Node 16 shipped OpenSSL 1.1.1)
#   - Optional Node builds with BoringSSL via
#     `./configure --shared-openssl-includes
#     +--shared-openssl-libpath` and similar
#   - Security advisories coordinated with the
#     OpenSSL project
#
# This is the *language-runtime-as-canonical-
# provider* pattern - parallel to Go's
# crypto/tls. Both Node + Go ship canonical TLS
# implementations as part of their language
# runtime/stdlib.
#
# However, Node's `tls` defers to OpenSSL (C
# code) rather than reimplementing TLS in
# JavaScript. This is the *FFI-canonical*
# pattern - Node ecosystem accepts the
# OpenSSL FFI dependency because pure-JS TLS
# would be prohibitively slow. Go's crypto/tls
# is the *pure-language-canonical* pattern
# where Go reimplements TLS in pure Go for
# memory safety + static binary deployment.
#
# Node's tls security history:
#   - Node 0.10 (2013): first stable TLS API
#   - Node 4.x (2015): TLS 1.2 default
#   - Node 12.x (2019): TLS 1.3 support
#   - Node 18.x (2022): OpenSSL 3.0 upgrade
#   - Node 22.x (2024): improved QUIC + HTTP/3
#     foundations
#   - Multiple OpenSSL CVE patches integrated
#     via Node's security release cycle
#
# redsmin uses node:tls in app.js + lib/
# Endpoint.js + lib/RedisClient.js:
#   ```js
#   var tls = require('tls');
#
#   // Connect to Redsmin cloud endpoint
#   var socket = tls.connect({
#       port: config.redsmin.port,        // 993
#       host: config.redsmin.hostname,   // ssl.redsmin.com
#       rejectUnauthorized:
#           config.redsmin.reject_unauthorized,
#       servername: config.redsmin.hostname,
#   }, function () {
#       // Connected to Redsmin cloud
#       socket.write(authHeader);
#   });
#
#   socket.on('data', function (chunk) {
#       // Forward chunk to local Redis client
#       redisClient.write(chunk);
#   });
#   ```
# The TLS tunnel multiplexes all local Redis
# client connections into a single outbound TLS
# connection to ssl.redsmin.com:993, with
# per-client connection IDs encoded in the
# protocol headers.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 273 :: TLS (Transport Layer Security)
#              libraries (TLS 1.2 + TLS 1.3 +
#              X.509 cert chain validation +
#              ALPN + SNI + session resumption)
# Round 1519 :: TS-Node slot 3 of 4 :: CLOSES Axis 273
#                                       (266th axis closed)
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : rustls/rustls               [R1517 _hxn]
#             (Joe Birr-Pixton + team;
#              pure-Rust; memory-safe)
#   Go      : crypto/tls (stdlib)         [R1518 _PR-DNSd]
#             (Go team; pure-Go;
#              language-as-canonical)
#   TS/Node : node:tls (stdlib)           [R1519 THIS FILE]
#             (Node team; OpenSSL C
#              wrapper; language-runtime-
#              as-canonical)
#
# node:tls closes Axis 273 with the
# *language-runtime-as-canonical via FFI
# wrapping* pattern. The three lanes
# demonstrate three distinct TLS-canonical
# architectures:
#
#   - Rust (rustls): individual-team-authored
#     pure-Rust canonical
#   - Go (crypto/tls): language-team-authored
#     pure-Go stdlib canonical
#   - Node (node:tls): language-team-maintained
#     C++ wrapper around OpenSSL canonical
#
# Each lane's mechanism reflects the host
# ecosystem's typical FFI tolerance + the
# maturity of pure-language cryptography:
#   - Rust: prefers pure-language for memory
#     safety + audit clarity
#   - Go: prefers pure-language for static
#     binaries + simpler deployment
#   - Node: relies on OpenSSL because pure-JS
#     crypto is too slow for production TLS
#
# This is the *first axis in the corpus where
# the Node canonical defers to a C library via
# FFI*. Most Node canonicals are pure-JS
# (Schlueter's libraries; nodeca's libraries;
# Sorhus's microlibs; etc.) or use minimal
# native addons via node-gyp (jszip uses pure-
# JS; sharp uses libvips via node-addon; node-
# midi uses rtmidi via node-gyp). TLS is the
# *first canonical axis where pure-JS would
# be prohibitively slow* + Node's stdlib
# explicitly wraps a C library (OpenSSL).
#
# Cross-language interop at the TLS wire-
# protocol level - all three lanes can act
# as TLS clients/servers + negotiate sessions
# with any compliant TLS endpoint.
#
# Use-case spectrum across the three lanes:
#   - hxn (Rust, rustls via reqwest's
#     rustls-tls): headless-Chrome screenshot
#     tool with TLS for pre-fetch URL
#     validation
#   - PR-DNSd (Go, crypto/tls): passive-
#     recursive DNS daemon with DoT (DNS-over-
#     TLS) server
#   - redsmin (Node, node:tls): Redis proxy
#     daemon establishing outbound TLS tunnel
#     to the Redsmin cloud GUI service
#
# Three lanes, three use-case shapes (web
# scraping + DNS infrastructure + Redis
# management), three TLS-canonical
# architectures (pure-Rust + pure-Go + C-FFI-
# Node), all converging on the IETF TLS
# 1.2 + TLS 1.3 spec.
#
# Axis 273 closes the round 1519 cycle - 266th
# axis closed total.
#
# Notable pattern: of the three canonical TLS
# lanes, only the Node lane uses FFI. This is
# the most-aggressive FFI dependency in any
# canonical-library axis of the corpus +
# represents a fundamental tradeoff in
# ecosystem design:
#   - Pure-language (Rust + Go): cleaner
#     audit history but reimplementation cost
#   - FFI-wrapped (Node): leverages OpenSSL's
#     25-year battle-tested implementation but
#     inherits OpenSSL's CVE history + the
#     burden of OpenSSL maintenance/upgrades
#
# Both approaches have merit + the choice
# reflects ecosystem culture rather than any
# objective superiority.
#
# Multi-axis canonical-Node author/org cohort
# extension (now spanning 17 distinct
# individuals/orgs):
#   - + Node.js project core team (node:tls +
#     node:crypto + node:net + node:http +
#     node:https + many others; THIS AXIS
#     extends the Node team's stdlib
#     canonical position alongside the Node
#     core members like James M Snell + Anna
#     Henningsen + Matteo Collina + Bert
#     Belder + many others)
#
# This is the first formal axis closure where
# the Node lane's canonical is the Node core
# team itself rather than an individual author
# or org-backed library.
# ============================================================================

_redsmin() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[print version]'
}

_redsmin "$@"
